i just had my basement drywalled and want to prime it but there is dust all over the walls from the sanding what is the easiest way to remove the dust someone told me to use a slightly damp cloth and wipe the walls any suggestions would be appreciated a slightly damp cloth or sponge will pick up the dust do not use anything wet hehehe if you squeeze it and water comes out its too wet to use the advantage of using a slightly damp cloth or sponge is that it makes the dust cling to it rather than just push it around or get it into the air a sponge mop works well or swifter pads and with the handle makes it easier on your back some painters tack cloths will work as well but that's more expensive hehehe have fun Menstrual cup Vacuum cleaner Fire fighting Textile manufacturing Drywall Motorcycle Car washing techniques Upholstery Plaster Pottery Mattress Toilet paper SpongeBob SquarePants Strap-on dildo Volleyball Condom Diving suit Fire extinguisher Seismic retrofit Compost Diatom Basement Dishwashing Chalkboard Plastic Drill bit Sponge Wok Climbing equipment Hamster Dry cleaning Tampon Linen Dinghy Car handling Thermal power station Aerial (dance move) Geology of the Zion and Kolob canyons area Little Britain Swamp cooler Carbon dioxide Solder Floppy disk Laserdisc M16 (rifle) Caving Dust Wallpaper Table saw Bicycle brake systems Kitesurfing The Vile Village Explosive material Vacuum Heckler & Koch G3 Kitchen Urinary incontinence Table tennis Swimming pool Disc brake Pok__mon Abilities Printmaking Cruising (maritime) Stratification (botany) Casting Clothing Carpet Backstroke Soap Gypsum Fossil fuel power plant Felt Iron Punt (boat) Handloading Tarpon Springs, Florida Drowning Geography of Spain Hat Bicycle Craps Menstrual cycle Equine conformation Hemp Internal ballistics Tri-Cities, Washington Breaststroke Sirocco Butterfly stroke Precipitation (meteorology) Chinchilla Collecting fossils Loudspeaker Great Sand Dunes National Park and Preserve Sanitary towel Fecal incont